At Katraj junction, a PMPML bus is standing idle on the road with passengers on board, but without a driver. This is a common sight and it poses a risk of a major accident at this intersection due to the driver's absence. The negligence of the drivers is apparent in this situation. Local depot managers and PMPML officials seem to be overlooking this issue.

The Indian player #ViratKohli revealed a terrible incident during his stay in Perth on Monday. The entire event involved someone breaking into the cricketer's hotel room while he was out. The entire break-in was recorded on camera, and all of Kohli's accessories and clothing were put on a show. The former captain of India asked the supporters to respect everyone's privacy and avoid using them as "commodities" for entertainment. He appeared obviously shaken. @virat.kohli

latestPosts.caption:
A 25-year-old software engineer living in an elite society in Pune's Kondhwa area was sexually assaulted by a man who entered her house, pretending to be a delivery boy on Wednesday evening. This incident has once again raised the issue of women's safety in Pune city. The accused sprayed the victim's face, knocked her unconscious and sexually assaulted her. After this, he took a selfie on her mobile and wrote a text saying "I had fun, I'll come again!" and fled. The police are investigating the incident.

(This Video is A Dramatic Representation of The Actual Incident)

The National Green Tribunal’s Western Zone bench in Pune has slammed the Maharashtra government over unchecked tourism in the ecologically fragile Kalsubai-Harishchandragad Wildlife Sanctuary during firefly season. Despite no official Kajava Festival since 2023, thousands still flock to the area, threatening this rare bioluminescent phenomenon.

A 24-year-old woman was violently attacked and harassed by three men on Baner Road around 1 AM on July 9. This comes just a year after a similar horrifying assault on a mother of two on Baner-Pashan Road.
How many more before action is taken seriously? Roads must be safe for everyone, especially women.

Sai Essen Developers has been slapped with a massive ₹20.13 crore penalty by the Pune district administration for unauthorised excavation of over 37,000 brass of murrum soil at their ‘Aishwaryam Hamara Abhiman’ project site in Chikhali. ETS surveys confirmed large-scale illegal mining on land survey numbers 72/1 and 94. The builder, Satish Bhimsen Agrawal, has denied the charges and plans to appeal.
